                            <div class="row"> 
                                <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 blog-content">
                                    <div class="media-body">
                <p>If you are in the market for a new water heater, you might want to consider a tankless water heater. These systems do not have a traditional water tank: instead, they heat up water whenever you need it. Call it “hot water on demand”.</p>

                <p><b>The main advantages of tank-less water heaters are:</b></p>                                        
                <ul class="list-unstyled">
                    <li><i class="fa fa-hand-o-right"></i> They cost more to purchase, but cost less to run – you don’t need to heat up a full tank of water every time you turn on the hot water faucet;</li>
                    <li><i class="fa fa-hand-o-right"></i> Never run out of hot water;</li>
                    <li><i class="fa fa-hand-o-right"></i> Last much longer than tank-type water heaters;</li>
                    <li><i class="fa fa-hand-o-right"></i> With fewer moving parts, requires less maintenance or repair;</li>
                    <li><i class="fa fa-hand-o-right"></i> No tank to leak or become rusted;</li>
                    <li><i class="fa fa-hand-o-right"></i> Can supply unlimited hot water to several faucets at a time;</li>
                    <li><i class="fa fa-hand-o-right"></i> Smaller “point-of-use” models are available: they are cheaper to buy and are made to deliver hot water to a single location, such as a kitchen or bathroom;</li>
                    <li><i class="fa fa-hand-o-right"></i> Smaller tankless water heaters can be concealed in a cabinet;</li>
                    <li><i class="fa fa-hand-o-right"></i> Less wastage of water.</li>
                    
                </ul>

